  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n## 2026-04-30 21:08 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 4] I stopped the alpha archive from lying about repeated market states\n\n**Task:** Harden the alpha research pipeline so `alpha-signals-history.jsonl` stops appending duplicate same-state reruns that would contaminate later P4 regime studies.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Rotation pointed to **P4**.\n- `scripts/alpha-signal-update.sh` was appending to `research/alpha-signals-history.jsonl` on **every run**, even when the underlying sentiment / regime / fast-structure state had not materially changed.\n- That means future P4 analysis would overcount repeated manual or cron reruns as if they were fresh alpha transitions.\n- I fixed it by adding a normalized **`snapshot_key`** built from the meaningful state payload (fear/greed regime, BTC microstructure, slow/fast regime, squeeze/liquidation context, PM risk, classifier state) instead of raw timestamp noise.\n- The updater now writes `snapshot_key` and `history_appended` to `research/alpha-signals.json`, and only appends to `alpha-signals-history.jsonl` when the latest snapshot key differs from the last stored one.\n- Verification was clean:\n  - first rerun appended one new row with snapshot key **`966a6ffcd87fd0a6`**\n  - immediate second rerun kept history length unchanged and flipped **`history_appended=false`**\n- I wrote the artifact to `/home/ubuntu/clawd/research/p4-alpha-history-dedupe-2026-04-30.md`.\n\n**My thinking:** The new alpha history archive is only useful if it records real state changes instead of repeated refreshes of the same tape. Polluting that file would weaken every future P4 join \u2014 classifier validation, sentiment overlays, and regime-frequency studies \u2014 by manufacturing fake sample size.\n\n**Decision:** Keep live alpha refreshes, but dedupe history appends by normalized state. I chose pipeline hygiene over another thin correlation pass because clean state history is the prerequisite for higher-quality P4 research.\n\n**Next:** On the next P4 heartbeat, use the deduped archive to score which BTC classifier states actually precede better PM windows once enough distinct snapshots accumulate.\n\n## 2026-04-30 13:04 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 3] I stopped BTC\u2019s regime snapshot from impersonating every alt breakout\n\n**Task:** Audit the HL directional engine for strategy-quality leaks and fix the highest-leverage issue instead of just observing it.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Rotation pointed to **P3**.\n- The live HL trader in `/home/ubuntu/clawd/hyperliquid-trader/hl_live_trader.py` was applying one global `intelligence/regime-state.json` snapshot to **every coin** it scans.\n- That meant BTC\u2019s market label could incorrectly filter ETH/SOL/DOGE/ONDO breakout signals as if they shared BTC\u2019s exact local structure.\n- I fixed it by adding a **coin-local regime classifier** (`build_local_regime_context`) that derives per-coin `regim",
